# tcc-ufsm-2020
**(en-us)**this is the repository for my bachelor's degree final project at [ufsm](https://www.ufsm.br/): a game
prototype made to explore the entity-component-system (ecs) architecture and procedural dungeon generation.
while the game is not full playable at the moment, it
Fulfills my expectations. a more professional development will occur independently in another
Repository, after my graduation.

**(en)**this is the repository of my course completion work (tcc) at [ufsm](https://www.ufsm.br/): a
prototype game designed to explore the *entity-component-system* (ecs) and
procedural generation of *dungeons*.
Although the game is not fully playable (or even fun) at the moment,
He meets my expectations. further development will occur independently
in another repository, after my graduation.

![in-game screen.](screenshot.png)

# Wait! i read your article from sbgames 2020! Where do i go?
[/src/map_gen/](https://github.com/pprobst/tcc-ufsm2020/tree/master/src/map_gen) contents all the algorithms presented in the article. they're
generally easy to follow, but for fully understanding wavefunctioncollapse it
would be wise to read gridbugs' [article](https://gridbugs.org/wave-function-collapse/) (my implementation directly derives from it) or karth & smith [research paper](https://adamsmith.as/papers/wfc_is_constraint_solving_in_the_wild.pdf).
keep in mind that the procgen pipelines are still far from perfect, and i'll
still keep working on them. i'm also working on the general game mechanics and
in the future i'll play with procedural narrative -- a new interest for me.

however, this is a game prototype (not a procedural dungeon generation tool!) and still not ready for playing. but if
You know your way around rust and want to fiddle with the procgen algorithms,
Feel free to do it!

if you want to contact me for whatever reason, send me an email. you can use the email on my github
profile or the one in the paper.

# Execution
first, [install and configure rush in your machine](https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch01-01-installation.html).

then, clone this repository, navigate to it and run ```load run```` from your terminal emulator.

Tell me if you have any problems.

while in-game:
- use the vi-keys to move or select targets.
- space for contextual action (e.g. open doors).
- 'i' to access inventory.
- 'e' to access equipment.
- 'z' to switch between melee/ranged weapons.
- 'f' to target and fire.
- 'r' to reload.

---

# Main goals (tcc)
or, _"it would be good if I did all that!_". Priority order, sort of.
- [x] structure the basics of [bracket-lib](https://github.com/thebracket/bracket-lib)
(rltk) + [specs](https://github.com/amethyst/specs/), using the tutorial developed by wolferson as a basis;
- [x] player movement @;
- [x] basic structure of a map;
- [x] separate file for rendering the map and entities;
- [x] fov system (_field-of-view_);
- [x] camera/viewport (divergences begin here);
- [x] implement a basic ui and take advantage to improve the game states;
- [x] mobs and basic structure of the combat system;
- [x] some constructive methods of map generation:
- [x] random walkers;
- [x] cellular automata (ca);
- [x] ensure connectivity.
- [x] bsp (binary space partitioning) dungeons;
- [x] diggers/tunnelers.
- [x] Final touches.
- [x] hybrid map generation system (pipeline) using
[wfc](https://github.com/mxgmn/wavefunctioncollapse) together with other algorithms;
- [x] load external map manually drawn;
- [x] apply wfc on the current map;
- [x] ensure connectivity by the flood-fill method (ca);
- [x] insertion of prefabricated structures into the map;
- [x] different themes of maps:
- [x] tdcl (top-down basement-like);
- [x] tdml (top-down mansion-like);
- [x] forests;
- [x] ruins;
- [x] wfc as external/internal architecture.
- [x] inventory and consumption of items;
- [x] equipment;
- [x] treasure chests;
- [x] selection of regions on the map to apply generation algorithms;
- [x] use [ron](https://github.com/ron-rs/ron) (not json) to structure the raws;
- [x] basic serialization/deserialization system using ron +
serde for mobs, items and colors.

Of course, as I develop, I may have to
change/enhance already marked checklist items. this is a natural process;
consider that marked items already have the _basic structure_ completed.

# Known problems, etc.
- the spawning system is far from adequate.
- distortion of the tiles depending on the resolution.
- some crashes occur from time to time in the stage of map generation.
- probable cause: access to map index 0 (not used).
- for now, wfc does not restart when there is contradiction (rare of occurrence).

# Contributions #
if you have any good idea or suggestion, feel free to open a
[_issue_](https://github.com/pprobst/tcc-ufsm2020/issues/new).

# References and inspirations
Look at my monograph file for the reference list. other github projects they had
portions of code used (or that served as the basis for something) are referenced in the form of comments in the relevant source files.

